{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7f021179-18fa-4b8d-9251-2b8901bef7d5","content":"With MTP enabled (`UseMicrosoftTestingPlatformRunner=true`), the VSTest `--filter` syntax is replaced by **tree-node filter** syntax.\n\n**Old (VSTest):**\n```\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~IntegrationTests&Category=Smoke\"\n```\n\n**New (MTP):**\n```\ndotnet test --treenode-filter \"/**/*IntegrationTests*[Category=Smoke]/**\"\n```\n\nKey syntax differences:\n\n| VSTest concept | MTP tree-node equivalent |\n|---|---|\n| `FullyQualifiedName~X` (contains) | `/**/*X*/**` (glob wildcards) |\n| `Category=Smoke` (trait) | `[Category=Smoke]` (property bracket) |\n| `&` (AND) | Combine on the same node path |\n\nThe `/**` at the start matches any assembly/namespace prefix, `*IntegrationTests*` matches the class node by name, `[Category=Smoke]` filters by trait on that node, and the trailing `/**` includes all tests underneath it.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b8e8a01b-0d0f-4903-8ea7-efa72de4070a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is migrating from xUnit v2 to xUnit v3 with Microsoft Testing Platform (MTP). The key differences for filtering:\n\n1. With xUnit v2 + VSTest adapter, `dotnet test --filter` uses VSTest filter syntax where `FullyQualifiedName~IntegrationTests` means \"contains\" and `Category=Smoke` matches the Trait.\n\n2. With xUnit v3 + MTP (`UseMicrosoftTestingPlatformRunner=true`), the `--filter` flag from `dotnet test` is passed differently. MTP uses `--treenode-filter` instead of the VSTest `--filter` syntax.\n   \nWith MTP, `dotnet test --filter` still works but the filter expression format changes—instead of VSTest's syntax, MTP expects a tree-node filter format like `--treenode-filter` with a path-based pattern such as `/**/*IntegrationTests*`. Writing tree-node filter syntax... I need to clarify the distinction between `--filter` and `--treenode-filter` when using MTP. With modern MTP-based test projects, `dotnet test --filter` automatically translates to the tree-node format, so the syntax I described earlier works directly. The tree-node filter expression combines the class name pattern with the trait filter in a single path: `/**/*IntegrationTests*[Category=Smoke]/**`. The trait is attached to the class node itself, so the filter `/**/*IntegrationTests*[Category=Smoke]/**` matches all tests under classes with \"IntegrationTests\" in their name that have the Category=Smoke trait.","outputTokens":1748,"requestId":"3407:386D1F:56315BA:5E59459:69F3FBB8"},"id":"155a8d5c-cfa3-4d15-a1c8-5e89c30f9f96","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:03:24.036Z","parentId":"32014308-0e4f-40af-bd5c-967959f7bd4e"}
